mode script

// Reproduction for issue #256: the garbager/codegen clones an owned local
// at its last use instead of moving it.
//
// In `build`, `val` is a named owned local whose last (and only) use is the
// FieldAssign `h.child = val` into an Own field. It should MOVE. Instead the
// codegen emits `Node_clone(val)` -- a deep clone that includes a Str_clone
// of the literal label, and Str_clone ALWAYS malloc+memcpy's the chars (even
// for a cap = TIL_CAP_LIT literal that has no char heap of its own). The
// original `val` is then freed. A *temporary* RHS (e.g.
// `h.child = make_node()`) moves and never clones -- that inconsistency is
// the bug, and it is exactly how #252 regressed the ASAN leak baseline.
//
// To surface the extra clone heap as an ASAN-reported leak, build()'s owned
// return is abandoned below (an inline temporary, never bound or freed),
// standing in for #252's real situation where the cloned tree rode along in
// the compiler's retained-but-never-freed program AST. After main returns,
// LeakSanitizer reports the abandoned allocations -- and the report points
// straight at `Node_clone` / `Str_clone` inside `build`, which a move would
// not produce.
//
// Observe it:
//   bin/til build --asan -o tmp/bug256 test/bug256.til
//   ASAN_OPTIONS=detect_leaks=1 tmp/bug256
//   ==> SUMMARY: AddressSanitizer: NN byte(s) leaked, with Str_clone /
//       Node_clone frames inside build().
//
// NOT YET wired into test/tests.til: it leaks on purpose and would fail the
// ASAN-clean suite until #256 is fixed.

Node := struct {
    own label : Str = ""
}

Holder := struct {
    own child : Node = Node()
}

build := func() returns Holder {
    val := Node(label = "bug256-distinctive-literal-payload-tag!!")
    mut h := Holder()
    // BUG #256: last use of the named local `val` -> should move, clones.
    h.child = val
    return h
}

// Abandon the owned return so the cloned heap leaks (see header).
println("bug256: ", build().child.label)
